member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Shared.CallbackMultiplexer
member.summary: A non-visual web control that lets you refresh one or more callback controls within the same callback event.

remarks.para: Note that in our documentation, a callback panel or panel usually refers to an instance of a and a callback control refers to any control that implements the interface.
A will usually suffice when you have to refresh a bunch of controls within a panel. But, there are other scenarios where you might need more control over the refresh process.
For example, you may want to send a custom callback event to the page, where you can either decide to refresh one or more callback controls or simply return some script for processing.
Note that there is no need to add multiple instances of this multiplexer control to the page. Though it would work without any problems, there is logically no need to do so.

member.name: E:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Shared.CallbackPanel.CallbackRefresh
member.summary: Server-side event that is fired with the client side args, just before the panel is redrawn during a callback.

remarks.para: Handle this event to change the contents of the panel according to the event args the client sent.
remarks.code: Protected Sub CallbackPanel1_CallbackRefresh(ByVal sender As Object, ByVal e As Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.CancellableCallbackEventArgs) If e.CallbackArgument = "something" Then ' label1 is within this CallbackPanel. Me.label1.Text = "Some other text" Else If e.CallbackArgument = "xyz" Then ' You don't want to update anything, so prevent refreshing. e.Cancel = True End If End Sub

member.name: P:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.Shared.DateTimeTextBox.CustomFormat
member.summary:
Gets / sets custom format string. Format patterns: "ffffff" - The fraction of a second in six-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated. "fffff" - The fraction of a second in five-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated. "dddd" - The full name of the day of the week. "MMMM" - The full name of the month. "yyyy" - The year in four digits, including the century. "ffff" - The fraction of a second in four-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated. "ddd" - The abbreviated name of the day of the week. "MMM" - The abbreviated name of the month. "fff" - The fraction of a second in three-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated.
The day of the month. Single-digit days will have a leading zero. "dd" - The day of the month. Single-digit days will have a leading zero. "MM" - The numeric month. Single-digit months will have a leading zero. "yy" - The year without the century. If the year without the century is less than 10, the year is displayed with a leading zero. "hh" - The hour in a 12-hour clock. Single-digit hours will have a leading zero. "HH" - The hour in a 24-hour clock. Single-digit hours will have a leading zero. "mm" - The minute. Single-digit minutes will have a leading zero. "ss" - The second. Single-digit seconds will have a leading zero. "ff" - The fraction of a second in double-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated.
The day of the month. Single-digit days will not have a leading zero. "d" - The day of the month. Single-digit days will not have a leading zero. "M" - The numeric month. Single-digit months will not have a leading zero. "y" - The year without the century. If the year without the century is less than 10, the year is displayed with no leading zero. "h" - The hour in a 12-hour clock. Single-digit hours will not have a leading zero. "H" - The hour in a 24-hour clock. Single-digit hours will not have a leading zero. "m" - The minute. Single-digit minutes will not have a leading zero. "s" - The second. Single-digit seconds will not have a leading zero. "f" - The fraction of a second in single-digit precision. The remaining digits are truncated. "tt" - The AM/PM designator defined in AMDesignator or PMDesignator, if any. "t" - The first character in the AM/PM designator defined in AMDesignator or PMDesignator, if any. ":" - The default time separator defined in TimeSeparator. "/" - The default date separator defined in DateSeparator.

member.name: T:Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.ImageProvider.ImageWebHandler
member.summary: Handler type used when is set to Handler. Please refer to MSDN documentation for additional details on HttpHandlers. When OutputFormat is set to Handler, the image does not generate any disk files. This can lead to better performance than when files are generated and written to disk. Handlers need to be specified in the HttpHandlers section of your Web.Config file.
member.remarks:
Typical web config setting is shown below:
<httpHandlers> <add verb="*" path="Syncfusion_image_generate.ashx" type="Syncfusion.Web.UI.WebControls.ImageProvider.ImageWebHandler,Syncfusion.Shared.Web"/> </httpHandlers>
The path can be a wildcard. The path is not really used. The image uses the prefix syncfusion_image_generate only. If you use a specific filename, this has to be it. The extension ashx is used by default (by convention for HttpHandlers). However, this can be changed using the property. If you use a custom extension, please note that additional IIS and ASP.NET related configuration will be required. Please refer to MSDN for additional information on this topic.
